If you have property already, you can omit the FXFormFieldDefaultValue and it will get its value directly from your property.

To intercept changes to homeinit, you can add an action, like this:

```
@{FXFormFieldKey: @"homeinit", FXFormFieldAction: "methodName:"}
```

The action is the name of a method that you want to call on your controller when the value changes. So in your controller, you'd add:

```
- (void)methodName:(id<FXFormFieldCell>)cell {
    BOOL homeinitValue = [cell.field.value boolValue];
}
```

By the way, FXForms can automatically infer the field title from the property name, so if you give your form properties human-readable names then you don't have to specify the FXFormFieldTitle for every field (e.g. if you call your version property "programVersion", then the title will be "Program Version".

